{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17575"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17575"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0,0.48,0,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71348"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10265"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"10084"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71348"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe post-absorptive state begins several hours after a meal when absorption of nutrients is complete and blood glucose levels start to decline.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the metabolic changes that occur during the post-absorptive state?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased insulin and decreased glucagon secretion","Increased insulin and increased glucagon secretion","Increased glucagon and decreased insulin secretion","No change in either hormone secretion","Increased insulin and decreased glucagon secretion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the post-absorptive state, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased glucagon and decreased insulin secretion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in response to falling blood glucose levels. This hormonal shift promotes glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis in the liver to maintain blood glucose homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased insulin and decreased glucagon secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern occurs during the absorptive state when blood glucose is elevated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased insulin and increased glucagon secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - These hormones have opposing actions and are not typically elevated simultaneously\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased insulin and decreased glucagon secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucagon must increase to maintain blood glucose when insulin decreases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo change in either hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Hormonal changes are necessary to maintain glucose homeostasis between meals\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese hormonal changes help mobilise stored energy sources and maintain blood glucose levels until the next meal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The post-absorptive state occurs 4-12 hours after eating when blood glucose levels begin to fall.","Glucagon secretion increases while insulin secretion decreases during the post-absorptive state.","The liver maintains blood glucose through glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis in the post-absorptive state."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17575"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T08:00:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T08:01:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10265"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71348"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes